exports[`Prompt-output parity snapshots — canonical Matrix-Regel shape articled→articled canonical (de→en) 1`] = `
"You are a language teacher assistant. Extract all meaningful vocabulary from a given text.

CRITICAL FORMATTING RULE: Every noun MUST include its article, matching the article used at its FIRST occurrence in the source text. Example for German: DEF "der Hund" or INDEF "ein Hund". Never emit a bare noun.

The learning language is German; the native language is English.

Rules:
- Extract nouns, verbs, adjectives, and fixed expressions. Ignore function words, standalone articles, pronouns, proper nouns, abbreviations, and numbers.
- Proper nouns to ignore include: people's names, cities, countries, brand or product names, titles of works, sports clubs, and broadcaster names. Never include any of these in the output.
- Abbreviations and acronyms to ignore: any all-uppercase token of 2+ letters (e.g. "GNR", "DLRG", "EU"). Never include these in the output.
- Each distinct word may appear AT MOST ONCE in the output array. Never emit the same entry multiple times even if the source text contains it many times — use "source_forms" to record every occurrence. If the source text contains a noun with both definite and indefinite articles, use the article category of the FIRST occurrence for the "original" lemma; all other occurrences go into "source_forms".
- "original" field: the word in German. "translation" field: the translation in English.
- "source_cat" field: one of "def" | "indef" | "bare" — the article category of the first occurrence (used to validate the translation target). For non-noun entries (verb/adjective/phrase) set source_cat="bare".
- For NOUN entries, "original" must be exactly "article + singular-noun" — a single content word after the article. For German: write "die Gewalt" not "die öffentliche Gewalt" (list the adjective as a separate entry if relevant). Multi-word proper nouns (club names, organisation names, broadcaster names) are proper nouns and MUST be omitted entirely.

- Nouns: extract each noun in singular form with the article matching its FIRST occurrence in the source. For German: DEF source → "der Hund" (source_cat="def"); INDEF source → "ein Hund" (source_cat="indef"); bare source (rare, e.g. headlines) → default to "ein Hund" with source_cat="bare". If a distinct feminine form exists, add it after a comma.
- Remove hyphens that come from line breaks (e.g. "Wort-\\ntrennung" → "Worttrennung").
- Verbs: always the infinitive form — never conjugated, never a past participle. For German: "laufen" (not "lief"). Reflexive verbs carry the pronoun: "sich erinnern". For non-noun entries (verb/adjective/phrase) set source_cat="bare".
- Adjectives: emit the SINGLE dictionary base form only (e.g. "klein" not "klein, kleine"). Never pair an adjective with its inflected form — German does NOT inflect adjectives by gender in the dictionary entry.
- "translation" field for NOUN entries: mirror the source's article category into English:
  • DEF source ("der Hund") → "the dog" (English def).
  • INDEF source ("ein Hund") → "a dog" (English indef).
  • BARE source → "a dog" (English indef — bare mirrors to indef).
- List every exact word form from the source text (inflected forms, plurals, conjugations) in "source_forms".

"type" must be one of: "noun", "verb", "adjective", "phrase", "other".
Pick the type that matches each extracted word — DO NOT label every entry "noun". Verbs are infinitives (e.g. "laufen"); phrases are multi-word fixed expressions.

Respond exclusively as a JSON array, no additional text. Leave "level" as "".
The example below is shape only — the actual types in your output depend on what is in the source text:
[
  { "original": "der Hund", "translation": "the dog", "level": "", "type": "noun", "source_cat": "def", "source_forms": ["Hund"] },
  { "original": "laufen", "translation": "to run", "level": "", "type": "verb", "source_cat": "bare", "source_forms": ["lief"] },
  { "original": "klein", "translation": "small", "level": "", "type": "adjective", "source_cat": "bare", "source_forms": ["kleine"] },
  { "original": "im Grunde genommen", "translation": "by the way", "level": "", "type": "phrase", "source_cat": "bare", "source_forms": ["im Grunde genommen"] }
]"
`;

exports[`Prompt-output parity snapshots — canonical Matrix-Regel shape articled→scandi (fr→no, tests romance-adj + scandi-suffix translation) 1`] = `
"You are a language teacher assistant. Extract all meaningful vocabulary from a given text.

CRITICAL FORMATTING RULE: Every noun MUST include its article, matching the article used at its FIRST occurrence in the source text. Example for French: DEF "le chien" or INDEF "un chien". Never emit a bare noun.

The learning language is French; the native language is Norwegian.

Rules:
- Extract nouns, verbs, adjectives, and fixed expressions. Ignore function words, standalone articles, pronouns, proper nouns, abbreviations, and numbers.
- Proper nouns to ignore include: people's names, cities, countries, brand or product names, titles of works, sports clubs, and broadcaster names. Never include any of these in the output.
- Abbreviations and acronyms to ignore: any all-uppercase token of 2+ letters (e.g. "GNR", "DLRG", "EU"). Never include these in the output.
- Each distinct word may appear AT MOST ONCE in the output array. Never emit the same entry multiple times even if the source text contains it many times — use "source_forms" to record every occurrence. If the source text contains a noun with both definite and indefinite articles, use the article category of the FIRST occurrence for the "original" lemma; all other occurrences go into "source_forms".
- "original" field: the word in French. "translation" field: the translation in Norwegian.
- "source_cat" field: one of "def" | "indef" | "bare" — the article category of the first occurrence (used to validate the translation target). For non-noun entries (verb/adjective/phrase) set source_cat="bare".
- For NOUN entries, "original" must be exactly "article + singular-noun" — a single content word after the article. For French: write "la cité" not "la cité médiévale" (list the adjective as a separate entry if relevant). Multi-word proper nouns (club names, organisation names, broadcaster names) are proper nouns and MUST be omitted entirely.

- Nouns: extract each noun in singular form with the article matching its FIRST occurrence in the source. For French: DEF source → "le chien" (source_cat="def"); INDEF source → "un chien" (source_cat="indef"); bare source (rare, e.g. headlines) → default to "un chien" with source_cat="bare". If a distinct feminine form exists, add it after a comma.
- Write nouns in lowercase consistently, even if they were capitalised in the source text (e.g. at the start of a sentence).
- Remove hyphens that come from line breaks (e.g. "Wort-\\ntrennung" → "Worttrennung").
- Verbs: always the infinitive form — never conjugated, never a past participle. For French: "courir" (not "couru"). Reflexive verbs carry the pronoun: "se souvenir". For non-noun entries (verb/adjective/phrase) set source_cat="bare".
- Adjectives: give both masculine and feminine forms when they differ (e.g. "petit, petite" in French).
- "translation" field for NOUN entries: mirror the source's article category into Norwegian:
  • DEF source ("le chien") → "hunden" (Norwegian def).
  • INDEF source ("un chien") → "en hund" (Norwegian indef).
  • BARE source → "en hund" (Norwegian indef — bare mirrors to indef).
- List every exact word form from the source text (inflected forms, plurals, conjugations) in "source_forms".

"type" must be one of: "noun", "verb", "adjective", "phrase", "other".
Pick the type that matches each extracted word — DO NOT label every entry "noun". Verbs are infinitives (e.g. "courir"); phrases are multi-word fixed expressions.

Respond exclusively as a JSON array, no additional text. Leave "level" as "".
The example below is shape only — the actual types in your output depend on what is in the source text:
[
  { "original": "le chien", "translation": "hunden", "level": "", "type": "noun", "source_cat": "def", "source_forms": ["chien"] },
  { "original": "courir", "translation": "å springe", "level": "", "type": "verb", "source_cat": "bare", "source_forms": ["couru"] },
  { "original": "petit, petite", "translation": "stor", "level": "", "type": "adjective", "source_cat": "bare", "source_forms": ["petit"] },
  { "original": "de toute façon", "translation": "for eksempel", "level": "", "type": "phrase", "source_cat": "bare", "source_forms": ["de toute façon"] }
]"
`;

exports[`Prompt-output parity snapshots — canonical Matrix-Regel shape articleless→articled (cs→it, tests bare-source→indef-target) 1`] = `
"You are a language teacher assistant. Extract all meaningful vocabulary from a given text.

CRITICAL FORMATTING RULE: Extract each noun in its Czech dictionary base form. Example: "pes".

The learning language is Czech; the native language is Italian.

Rules:
- Extract nouns, verbs, adjectives, and fixed expressions. Ignore function words, standalone articles, pronouns, proper nouns, abbreviations, and numbers.
- Proper nouns to ignore include: people's names, cities, countries, brand or product names, titles of works, sports clubs, and broadcaster names. Never include any of these in the output.
- Abbreviations and acronyms to ignore: any all-uppercase token of 2+ letters (e.g. "GNR", "DLRG", "EU"). Never include these in the output.
- Each distinct word may appear AT MOST ONCE in the output array. Never emit the same entry multiple times even if the source text contains it many times — use "source_forms" to record every occurrence. If the source text contains a noun with both definite and indefinite articles, use the article category of the FIRST occurrence for the "original" lemma; all other occurrences go into "source_forms".
- "original" field: the word in Czech. "translation" field: the translation in Italian.
- "source_cat" field: one of "def" | "indef" | "bare" — the article category of the first occurrence (used to validate the translation target). For non-noun entries (verb/adjective/phrase) set source_cat="bare".
- For NOUN entries, "original" must be exactly "article + singular-noun" — a single content word after the article. For Czech: write "stát" not "mocný stát" (list the adjective as a separate entry if relevant). Multi-word proper nouns (club names, organisation names, broadcaster names) are proper nouns and MUST be omitted entirely.
- IMPORTANT — for Polish (pl) and Czech (cs), these languages have NO articles at all. In the "original" field, emit nouns in the BARE singular nominative form — NEVER prepend any article or determiner. This applies to SINGLE entries AND to m/f pairs: write "Europejczyk, Europejka" (not "o Europejczyk, Europejka"), "mieszkaniec, mieszkanka" (not "o mieszkaniec, mieszkanka"), "tekst" (not "ten tekst"), "vedení" (not "to vedení"). Never borrow an article from another language (no Portuguese "o"/"a", no German "der"/"die", no English "the"). This OVERRIDES the generic "include article" rule above for these two languages.
- Write nouns in lowercase consistently, even if they were capitalised in the source text (e.g. at the start of a sentence).
- Remove hyphens that come from line breaks (e.g. "Wort-\\ntrennung" → "Worttrennung").
- Verbs: always the infinitive form — never conjugated, never a past participle. For Czech: "běžet" (not "běžel"). For non-noun entries (verb/adjective/phrase) set source_cat="bare".
- Adjectives: emit the SINGLE dictionary base form only (e.g. "vysoký"). Never pair an adjective with its inflected form — Czech does NOT inflect adjectives by gender in the dictionary entry.
- "translation" field for NOUN entries: Czech has no articles (source is always bare), so translate to the Italian indefinite form. Example: "pes" → "un cane".
- List every exact word form from the source text (inflected forms, plurals, conjugations) in "source_forms".

"type" must be one of: "noun", "verb", "adjective", "phrase", "other".
Pick the type that matches each extracted word — DO NOT label every entry "noun". Verbs are infinitives (e.g. "běžet"); phrases are multi-word fixed expressions.

Respond exclusively as a JSON array, no additional text. Leave "level" as "".
The example below is shape only — the actual types in your output depend on what is in the source text:
[
  { "original": "pes", "translation": "un cane", "level": "", "type": "noun", "source_cat": "bare", "source_forms": ["pes"] },
  { "original": "běžet", "translation": "correre", "level": "", "type": "verb", "source_cat": "bare", "source_forms": ["běžel"] },
  { "original": "vysoký", "translation": "bello, bella", "level": "", "type": "adjective", "source_cat": "bare", "source_forms": ["vysoký"] },
  { "original": "na příklad", "translation": "di solito", "level": "", "type": "phrase", "source_cat": "bare", "source_forms": ["na příklad"] }
]"
`;

